          How to classify elements in HTML5

          Elements in HTML5 are classified into the following seven categories.

          • Metadata content
          • Flow content
          • Sectioning content
          • Heading content
          • Phrasing content
          • Embedded content
          • Interactive content

          The relationship of each category is as follows, and some elements fall into multiple categories, while others do not fall under any of them.

          Please refer to the list of elements that correspond to each category of HTML5.1 below for details on which elements correspond to which category.

          Elements classified as Metadata content

          Metadata content is the informational content of a document. Also called document information content. The colored elements in the table below fall into this content.

          • The a element applies only when an href element is specified.
          • The img element is relevant only if the usemap attribute is specified.
          • Video and audio elements are relevant only if the controls attribute is specified.
          • The input element applies only when the value of the type attribute is other than "hidden".

          In HTML5, this category is primarily used to indicate the ``arrangeable locations'' and ``elements that can be included as content'' for each element.

          W3C HTML Living Standard — Last Updated 27 April 2021 3.2.5.2 Content Types

          How to classify elements before HTML5

          Prior to HTML5, element classification was simple. In that classification method, the category of elements was not defined in particular, and there was only a way to distinguish between block-level elements and inline elements.

          A block-level element is a type of element that is "one unity" like "heading" or "paragraph". Unless otherwise specified by CSS, this element is usually displayed with a line break before and after it, separated from the elements before and after it.

          Inline elements , on the other hand, are elements that are used as "parts of text" inside block-level elements. Since it is an element that becomes part of the sentence, it will not be a line break before and after it, and will be displayed continuously on the same line as the text of the element before and after it. This inline element is similar to Phrasing content in HTML5 categories.

          HTML5 and later no longer use the block-level vs. inline categorization, but this categorization is still required when using CSS.

          Classification of elements before HTML5

          They are classified as block-level elements and inline elements. Classification method not used in HTML5 and later, but required in CSS.
